y tradition. The book examines the various ethical gaps between just war theory and the legal and moral status of AWS, addresses the limits of both traditional and revisionist just war theory, and proposes ways of bridging some of these gaps. It adopts a dualistic notion of moral responsibility—or differing, related notions of moral responsibility and legitimate authority—to study the conflicts and contradictions of legitimizing the autonomous weapons that are designed to secure peace and neutralize the effects of violence. Focusing on the changing conditions and dynamics of accountability, responsibility, autonomy, and rights in twenty-first-century warfare, the volume sheds light on the effects of violence and the future ethics of modern warfare.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aArtificial intelligencexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aAutonomous weapons systemszUnited States. 0aJust war doctrine. 0aMilitary roboticsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMilitary robotsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMilitary weaponsxTechnological innovationsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aWeapons systemsxTechnological innovationszUnited States. 4aPhilosophy : Ethics. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aScience, Mathematics, and Technology : Science and Society. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBolia, Robert S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle II, Thomas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckert, Amy E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckert, Amy E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGalliott, Jai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunkel, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, 